Let $\theta =\arcsin\left(\frac{\sqrt{9-x^2}}{3}\right)$. Then
$\sin(\theta) =\frac{\sqrt{9-x^2}}{3}$. This gives the following
triangle:

\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH102/December_2013/Math102December2013A2real.jpg}

To solve for the last side, we simply use the Pythagorean
theorem\begin{align*}
a^{2} = 3^{2} - \left(\sqrt{9-x^{2}}\right)^2 = 9-9+x^{2} = x^{2}
\end{align*}
and so $a=x$ (we only need to consider the positive root since $a$ has
to be positive).

Hence, taking the cosine of theta in our triangle above, we see that
$\cos(\theta) = \cos\left(\arcsin\left(\frac{\sqrt{9-x^2}}{3}\right)\right) = \frac{a}{3} = \frac{x}{3}$,
which is answer ${\color{blue}\text{(B)}}$.
